- OOPs stands for Object-Oriented Programming System. It is a way of structuring code so that objects represent entities,
  and interactions between them solve problems.
  It focuses on modeling real-world entities by combining data (attributes) and behavior (methods) into a single unit.

fully oops languages: scala, ruby
partial oops languages: java, javascript, python, c#, c++

Why OOP Matters in Java:
- Modularity: Breaks complex problems into smaller units.
- Reusability: Inherited code reduces duplication.
- Scalability: Easier to extend and maintain.
- Security: Encapsulation protects sensitive data.

1. Encapsulation
- Bundling data (fields) and methods (functions) into a single unit (class).
- Restricts direct access to data using access modifiers (private, public, protected).
- Achieved through getters and setters.
- Example:
    class Student {
        private String name;
        public String getName() { return name; }
        public void setName(String name) { this.name = name; }
    }

2. Inheritance
- Enables a class (child) to acquire properties and behaviors of another class (parent).
- Promotes code reusability.
- Uses the extends keyword.
- Example:
    class Animal {
        void sound() { System.out.println("Animal makes sound"); }
    }
    class Dog extends Animal {
        void sound() { System.out.println("Dog barks"); }
    }

3. Polymorphism
- Means "many forms."
- Allows methods to behave differently based on context.
- Two types:
- Compile-time (Method Overloading)
- Runtime (Method Overriding)
- Example:
    class MathUtils {
        int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }
        double add(double a, double b) { return a + b; } // overloading
    }

4. Abstraction
- Hides implementation details and shows only essential features.
- Achieved using abstract classes and interfaces.
- Example:
    abstract class Shape {
        abstract void draw();
    }
    class Circle extends Shape {
        void draw() { System.out.println("Drawing Circle"); }
    }
















